# Bun Package Manager Rules

## Required Package Manager
- **MUST use Bun** for all Node.js package management operations
- **NEVER use npm, pnpm, or yarn** commands

## Commands to Use

### Installation
- Use `bun install` (never `npm install`, `pnpm install`, or `yarn install`)
- Use `bun add <package>` to add dependencies (never `npm install <package>`, `pnpm add <package>`, or `yarn add <package>`)
- Use `bun add -d <package>` for dev dependencies (never `npm install --save-dev`, `pnpm add -D`, or `yarn add -D`)

### Scripts
- Run scripts with `bun run <script>` (never `npm run`, `pnpm run`, or `yarn run`)
- For scripts defined in `package.json`, use `bun <script-name>`

### Other Operations
- Use `bun remove <package>` to remove packages (never `npm uninstall`, `pnpm remove`, or `yarn remove`)
- Use `bun update` to update packages (never `npm update`, `pnpm update`, or `yarn upgrade`)

## Package Lock Files
- Use `bun.lockb` (Bun's lockfile format)
- Do NOT commit `package-lock.json` (npm), `pnpm-lock.yaml` (pnpm), or `yarn.lock` (yarn)

## Best Practices
- Always verify Bun is installed: `bun --version`
- When suggesting package installation or script execution, always use Bun commands
- If npm/pnpm/yarn commands appear in code or documentation, suggest replacing them with Bun equivalents